|1||0||2||0||38||3\n|-\n|[[1996\u201397 in English football|1996\u201397]]\n|Third Division\n|10||1||0||0||1||0||0||0||11||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!44!!4!!1!!0!!2!!0!!2!!0!!49!!4\n|-\n|[[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]] (loan)\n|[[1996\u201397 in English football|1996\u201397]]\n|Third Division\n|3||0||0||0||0||0||0||0||3||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career Total\n!178!!22!!3!!0!!13!!3!!14!!3!!208!!28\n|}\n\n{{refbegin}}\n:A.&nbsp;{{note|Other}} The \"Other\" column constitutes appearances and goals in the [[Anglo-Italian Cup]], [[Football League play-offs]] and [[Football League Trophy]].\n{{refend}}\n\n==Honours==\n; Stoke City\n* [[Football League Second Division]] champions: [[1992\u201393 Stoke City F.C. season|1992\u201393]]\n* [[Football League Trophy]] winner: [[1992 Football League Trophy Final|1992]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-24650247 Interview with Kelly on his gambling addiction] with the [[BBC]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kelly, Tony}}\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Coventry]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Stoke City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hull City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Cardiff City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bury F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leyton Orient F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bristol City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Colchester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Nuneaton Borough F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stratford Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dulwich Hamlet F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Corinthian-Casuals F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Cheshunt F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Enfield Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:St Albans City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Falkirk F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Harlow Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Black English sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people|Tony Kelly}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Tony Kelly\n| image          = \n| fullname       = Nyrere Anthony Okpara Kelly<ref name=\"Stoke City Modern Era\"/>\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1966|2|14|df=y}}<ref name=\"Stoke City Modern Era\"/>\n| birth_place    = [[Coventry]], England<ref name=\"Stoke City Modern Era\"/>\n| death_date     = \n| youthyears1    = 1980\u20131982| youthclubs1 = [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]\n| position       = [[Forward (association football)|Winger]]\n| years1         = 1982\u20131983 | clubs1  = [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]                    |caps1  = 6    |goals1  = 1\n| years2         = 1983      | clubs2  = [[Nuneaton Town F.C.|Nuneaton Borough]]               |caps2  =      |goals2  = \n| years3         = 1983\u20131985 | clubs3  = [[Stratford Town F.C.|Stratford Town]]                |caps3  =      |goals3  = \n| years4         = 1985\u20131986 | clubs4  = [[Dulwich Hamlet F.C.|Dulwich Hamlet]]                |caps4  =      |goals4  =\n| years5         = 1987      | clubs5  = [[Corinthian-Casuals F.C.|Corinthian-Casuals]]        |caps5  =      |goals5  =  \n| years6         = 1987\u20131988 | clubs6  = [[Cheshunt F.C.|Cheshunt]]                            |caps6  =      |goals6  = \n| years7         = 1988      | clubs7  = [[Enfield Town F.C.|Enfield Town]]                    |caps7  =      |goals7  = \n| years8         = 1988\u20131990 | clubs8  = [[St Albans City F.C.|St Albans City]]                |caps8  =      |goals8  = \n| years9         = 1989      | clubs9  = \u2192 [[Gimon\u00e4s CK]] (loan)                               |caps9  =      |goals9  = \n| years10        = 1990\u20131993 | clubs10 = [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]                        |caps10 = 58   |goals10 = 5\n| years11        = 1991\u20131992 | clubs11 = \u2192 [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] (loan)               |caps11 = 6    |goals11 = 1\n| years12        = 1992\u20131993 | clubs12 = \u2192 [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] (loan)           |caps12 = 5    |goals12 = 1\n| years13        = 1993\u20131995 | clubs13 = [[Bury F.C.|Bury]]                                    |caps13 = 56   |goals13 = 10\n| years14        = 1995\u20131997 | clubs14 = [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]]                  |caps14 = 44   |goals14 = 4\n| years15        = 1996      | clubs15 = \u2192 [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]] (loan) |caps15 = 3    |goals15 = 0\n| years17        = 1997      | clubs17 = [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]]                              |caps17 = 1    |goals17 = 0\n| years18        = 1997\u20131998 | clubs18 = [[St Albans City F.C.|St Albans City]]                |caps18 =      |goals18 = \n| years19        = 1998\u20131999 | clubs19 = [[Harlow Town F.C.|Harlow Town]]                      |caps19 =      |goals19 =\n| totalcaps = 179 | totalgoals = 22\n}}\n'''Nyrere Anthony Okpara''' \"'''Tony'''\" '''Kelly''' (born 14 February 1966) is an English former [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|winger]].<ref name=\"Stoke City Modern Era\">{{cite book|last=Lowe|first=Simon|title=Stoke City The Modern Era \u2013 A Complete Record|year=2000|publisher=Desert Island Books|isbn=1-874287-39-2}}</ref>\n\nKelly began his career with [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] but after failing to establish himself in the first team he entered non-league football. He played for [[Nuneaton Town F.C.|Nuneaton Borough]], [[Stratford Town F.C.|Stratford Town]], [[Dulwich Hamlet F.C.|Dulwich Hamlet]], [[Corinthian-Casuals F.C.|Corinthian-Casuals]], [[Cheshunt F.C.|Cheshunt]], [[Enfield Town F.C.|Enfield Town]], [[Gimon\u00e4s CK]] (Sweden) and [[St Albans City F.C.|St Albans City]].\n\nHe joined [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] in January 1990 and at the [[Victoria Ground]] Kelly was never a regular but did play in the [[1992 Football League Trophy Final]] victory over [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]]. After loan spells at [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] and [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] he signed permanently with [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] and later played with [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]], [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]], [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]] and made a return to [[St Albans City F.C.|St Albans City]] before ending his career at [[Harlow Town F.C.|Harlow Town]]. Throughout his career Kelly struggled with a [[Problem gambling|gambling addiction]] and ran up debts of over \u00a3300,000.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\nKelly was born in [[Coventry]] and was one of seven children including his twin brother Mel.<ref name=\"RC\">{{cite book|last=Kelly|first=Tony|title=Red Card|year=2013|publisher=Mereo Books|isbn=9781909544703}}</ref> They both went to the same school in the [[Tile Hill]] area of the city before they moved to [[Coundon, Coventry|Coundon]] on the other side of the city. After playing football with the school team Kelly and his brother joined a [[Sunday league football|Sunday League]] side, Coundon Cockerels managed by a Scotsman, Dave McLeod.<ref name=\"RC\"/> Two of his other brothers were also involved with football, Abby who played in non-league and [[Errington Kelly|Errington]] who made it as a professional.<ref name=\"RC\"/> He moved to Woodlands Secondary School and his PE teacher recommended him to play for the Coventry schoolboys.<ref name=\"RC\"/> At high school Kelly had to deal with racist abuse and often got into fights. Kelly became friends with boxer [[Errol Christie]] which made going to nightclubs easier.<ref name=\"RC\"/>\n\nOne day his brother Errington, who was playing for [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] set him and Mel up with a trial.<ref name=\"RC\"/> The pair travelled with Errington to [[Bristol]] where they met the Rovers manager [[Bobby Gould]] and after a couple of training sessions they played in a [[South East Counties League]] match against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].<ref name=\"RC\"/> However it was not enough for them to be offered a contract by Bristol Rovers.<ref name=\"RC\"/> Errington then asked his former manager [[Terry Cooper (footballer born 1944)|Terry Cooper]] who was now at [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] if they could have a trial and he accepted. They both played and scored in a trial match against [[Mangotsfield United F.C.|Mangotsfield United]] which saw them both successfully offered a [[Youth Training Scheme|YTS]] at the club.<ref name=\"RC\"/> After meeting with the rest of the squad they moved into a lodgings paid by the club to accommodate youth team players and he was informed that his behavior would be closely monitored.\n\nKelly began to impress the coaches at [[Ashton Gate Stadium|Ashton Gate]] and he began to train with the first team and on 16 October 1982 he was named in the squad for a league match away at [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]].<ref name=\"RC\"/> He came on as a second-half substitute in a 1\u20131 draw and at the age of 16 years and 244 days he became Bristol City's youngest player. His record remained until it was broken by [[Marvin Brown]] in 1999. Kelly then played against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] at [[Hillsborough Stadium|Hillsborough]] in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] in a narrow 2\u20131 defeat. His brother Mel was struggling to make an impact and was released by the club in November 1982. It was at this time Kelly began to 'get too big for his boots' and began to show a poor attitude which did not go unnoticed by the management who sent him back to the youth team.<ref name=\"RC\"/> He earned a recall to the first team against [[Hereford United F.C.|Hereford United]] on 28 December 1982 where he scored his first league goal in a 3\u20131 victory.<ref name=\"RC\"/> However, by 1983 he was not being asked to play and in May 1983 he was informed by Terry Cooper he was being released because of his \"rubbish attitude\" and so Kelly returned to his family in Coventry.<ref name=\"RC\"/>\n\n===Non-league football===\nAfter returning to Coventry, Kelly contacted local non-league sides [[Nuneaton Town F.C.|Nuneaton Borough]] and [[Bedworth United F.C.|Bedworth United]] in the hope of getting the chance to play football again and after a short trial he joined Nuneaton Borough.<ref name=\"RC\"/> Under the management of [[Graham Carr]] Nuneaton played in the [[Conference Premier|Alliance Premier League]] and it was hard for Kelly to establish himself in the first team and when Carr could not offer Kelly a long-term contract he wanted he parted amicably for [[Stratford Town F.C.|Stratford Town]].<ref name=\"RC\"/> At Stratford was his brother Abby and together they played in the [[Midland Football Combination|Midland Combination League]] whilst he also worked as a banqueting porter at the Hotel Leofric. In the summer of 1983 Kelly began to visit his brother, Mel who had moved to [[London]] and was now playing for [[Dulwich Hamlet F.C.|Dulwich Hamlet]]. After starting the 1984\u201385 season with Stratford Kelly moved to London in March 1985 and got a job as a security guard in [[Dulwich]].<ref name=\"RC\"/>\n\nHe also began playing for Dulwich Hamlet whose first-team included [[Alan Pardew]], [[Andy Gray (footballer, born 1964)|Andy Gray]] and [[Paul Harding (association footballer)|Paul Harding]] but Mel soon left for [[Corinthian-Casuals F.C.|Corinthian-Casuals]]. It was at this time Kelly began to get involved with gambling and would soon become an addiction.<ref name=\"RC\"/> In January 1987 he moved in with his sister, Pat in [[London Borough of Enfield|Enfield]] and signed for Corinthian-Casuals. On his 21st birthday Kelly was playing in an away match where he was sent-off for two bookable offences and in rage Kelly pushed the referee to the ground. Kelly was given a nine-month ban by the FA and he left Corinthian-Casuals and also decided to change his name from Nyrere to Tony.<ref name=\"RC\"/>\n\nHe began playing with [[Cheshunt F.C.|Cheshunt]] where he finished the 1987\u201388 season as top-scorer and also changed his name again this time to Nyrere Anthony Okpara Kelly.<ref name=\"RC\"/> He then had a brief spell with [[Enfield Town F.C.|Enfield Town]] before joining [[St Albans City F.C.|St Albans City]]. By now his brother [[Errington Kelly|Errington]] had moved to Sweden to play for [[Grebbestads IF]] and after Kelly went over to visit him he began writing to Swedish clubs's offering them his services. To his surprise St Albans received a loan offer from [[Swedish Football Division 2|Swedish Second Division]] side [[Gimon\u00e4s CK]] which Kelly quickly accepted.<ref name=\"RC\"/>\n\nGimon\u00e4s is based in the city of [[Ume\u00e5]] and Kelly travelled there with the intentions of attracting the attentions of top-flight Swedish teams and teams back in England. Errington also managed to make the move to Gimon\u00e4s and the club under the management of [[Anders Johansson (footballer)|Anders Johansson]] had ambitions to aim for promotion to the [[Allsvenskan]].<ref name=\"RC\"/> However results were inconsistent and they ended the [[1989 Swedish football Division 2|season]] in 6th position. With his loan spell coming to an end St Albans decided against extended it and so Kelly returned to England in November 1989.<ref name=\"RC\"/> On his return to London, Kelly resumed his job at Eastern Electricity and also continued to go to betting shops and play for St Albans City.<ref name=\"RC\"/>\n\nHis time in Sweden had alerted other clubs to his talents and he earned a trial at [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]. He had two training sessions with the Saints squad and played in a reserve match against [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]] and whilst Kelly impressed the manager [[Chris Nicholl]] he could not justify paying the \u00a3100,000 St Albans wanted so Kelly returned to the club to have words with chairman Bernard Tominey. St Albans refused to lower their demands but decided they would accept \u00a340,000 from a club not in the First Division.<ref name=\"RC\"/> Kelly then played a trial match for [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] but picked up an injury which scuppered any move. He was then told [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] were interested and that their manager [[Alan Ball, Jr.|Alan Ball]] would be attending their next match against [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]].<ref name=\"RC\"/> Assistant manager [[Graham Paddon]] contacted Kelly the next day offering him a trial but Kelly refused and stated he wants a contract. Ball soon rang back and offered him a two and a half year deal for a fee of \u00a320,000 which St Albans accepted.<ref name=\"RC\"/>\n\n===Stoke City===\nKelly joined Stoke in January 1990 with the team struggling at the foot of the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]]. After he moved to [[Stoke-on-Trent]] from London he was shown around the [[Victoria Ground]] and was given free accommodation at a local hotel and he was also given a \u00a310,000 signing on fee but he spent most of it gambling. He made his debut for Stoke in the [[Potteries derby]] against [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] on 3 February 1990 where he played 70 minutes in a goalless draw at [[Vale Park]]. In all he made nine appearances in [[1989\u201390 Stoke City F.C. season|1989\u201390]] as Stoke dropped into the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]]. In [[1990\u201391 Stoke City F.C. season|1990\u201391]] Kelly struggled to become a regular in the side under [[Alan Ball, Jr.|Alan Ball]] with most of his appearances coming off the substitute bench.<ref name=\"Stoke City Modern Era\"/> Ball was sacked by Stoke in February 1991 and was replaced by [[Lou Macari]] in June 1991.\n\nMacari's intense fitness sessions worked well with Kelly who made his biggest contribution in a Stoke shirt on 25 September 1991 when he scored a late equaliser in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] at [[Anfield]]. However his joy soon turned to despair as in the second leg a Kelly backpass was intercepted by [[Ian Rush]] and Liverpool went on to win 3\u20132. Stoke pushed for promotion in [[1991\u201392 Stoke City F.C. season|1991\u201392]] and they reached the [[Football League play-offs|play-offs]] where they lost to [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]]. Three days later the two sides met again this time in the [[Football League Trophy]] [[1992 Football League Trophy Final|final]] at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]] a [[Mark Stein (footballer)|Mark Stein]] goal earning Stoke a 1\u20130 win. He played nine times in [[1992\u201393 Stoke City F.C. season|1992\u201393]] as Stoke won the Second Division title. His gambling addiction caused him to lose his form and after failing to play in [[1993\u201394 Stoke City F.C. season|1993\u201394]] Macari decided to move Kelly on. Whilst out of the side he spent time out on loan at [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] (making six appearances scoring once) and [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] (making five appearances scoring once).<ref name=\"Stoke City Modern Era\"/>\n\n===Later career===\nKelly joined [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] in September 1993 playing 37 times in [[1993\u201394 in English football|1993\u201394]] scoring eight goals and then helped the \"Shakers\" reach the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] play-offs in [[1995 Football League Third Division play-off Final|1995]] losing 2\u20130 to [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]] in the final. He then signed for [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] for a fee of \u00a340,000 and he played in 38 matches in [[1995\u201396 in English football|1995\u201396]] as the Os finished in 21st position. In [[1996\u201397 in English football|1996\u201397]] he fell out with manager [[Pat Holland]] and was sent out on loan to [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]] for whom he made three appearances. On his return to [[Brisbane Road]] Kelly turned down the chance to go on loan to Watford and went on to play 11 times for Orient in 1996\u201397.<ref name=\"RC\"/>\n\nWith his gambling debts now up to \u00a3300,000 Kelly decided to retire from football but he postponed it to play in Scotland with [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]].<ref name=\"RC\"/> However, after just one appearance he quickly returned to London and signed a two-year deal with St Albans. Whilst at St Albans he worked as a part-time agent with Mel and helped his cousin [[Leon Kelly (footballer)|Leon]] earn a professional contract at [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]].<ref name=\"RC\"/> Kelly ended his career with an 18-month spell at [[Harlow Town F.C.|Harlow Town]] before retiring and later went to work for [[Network Rail]].<ref name=\"RC\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nKelly suffered with a severe [[Problem gambling|gambling addiction]] during his career, and ran up debts of \u00a3300,000 before being declared bankrupt.<ref>{{cite news|last=Woods|first=David|title=Gordon Taylor's aid for Tony Kelly's gambling addiction book|url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/sport/football/335483/exclusive-gordon-taylor-s-aid-for-tony-kelly-s-gambling-addiction-book|accessdate=7 September 2013|newspaper=Daily Star|date=30 August 2013}}</ref> He wrote a book, largely about his addiction and his career, entitled ''Red Card'' in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Red Card|url=http://www.memoirspublishing.com/Books%20Pages/tonykelly-redcar.html|work=memoirspublishing.com|accessdate=7 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=It became normal to lose \u00a3500 in an hour|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/tony-kelly---became-normal-5802334|work=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=28 September 2013}}</ref> His brother [[Errington Kelly|Errington]] was also a professional footballer.\n\n==Career statistics==\nSourced from {{ENFA}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|FA Cup\n!cols