{"title_page": "Screencheat", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = Screencheat\n| image = Screencheat Logo.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = ''Screencheat''s logo\n| developer = Samurai Punk\n| publisher = Surprise Attack\n| series = \n| engine = [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]]\n| platforms = {{Unbulleted list|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[OS X]]|[[Linux]]|[[PlayStation 4]]|[[Xbox One]]|[[Nintendo Switch]]}}\n| released = {{ubl|'''Windows''', '''OS X''', '''Linux'''|21 October 2014|'''PS4''', '''Xbox One'''|1 March 2016|'''Nintendo Switch'''|29 November 2018}}\n| genre = [[First-person shooter]]\n| modes = [[Singleplayer]],  [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Screencheat''''' is a [[first-person shooter]] [[video game]] developed by Samurai Punk and published by Surprise Attack. The game was released for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[OS X]], and [[Linux]] in October 2014 and was released for [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]] in March 2016. The game was later ported to [[Nintendo Switch]], with enhanced graphics and updated interface, under the name '''''Screencheat: Unplugged''''', in November 2018.\n\n==Gameplay==\n''Screencheat'' is a [[multiplayer]] [[first-person shooter]] video game, in which every player's character model is invisible. However, the viewpoints of all players are shown on the screen, encouraging players [[Glossary of video game terms#screen cheat|to use this feature to deduce their opponents' location]].<ref name=\"ign_beta\" /> The maps are brightly colored in order to make it easier to figure out where a player is.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/03/04/screencheat-review-split-screen-revenge-5732508/|title=Games review: Screencheat is a celebration of split-screen gaming|last=Metro.co.uk|first=GameCentral for|date=2016-03-04|website=Metro|access-date=2017-03-24}}</ref>\n\n''Screencheat'' includes several different gamemodes. Some, including Deathmatch, King of the Hill, and Capture the Fun (where players fight for possession of a pi\u00f1ata), are multiplayer FPS standards.  The game also has a handful of unique gamemodes, such as One Shot, where each player is limited to one shot and cannot reload until a certain amount of time, and Murder Mystery, in which players have to kill a specific opponent with a particular weapon.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Development and release==\n''Screencheat'' was developed by Australia-based studio Samurai Punk and published by Surprise Attack.<ref name=\"ign_beta\" /> The game{{'}}s inception came from the 2014 [[Global Game Jam]], where it received several awards and honourable mentions.<ref name=\"ign_beta\" /> The game was released for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[OS X]], and [[Linux]] on 21 October 2014.<ref name=\"ign_pc_release_date\" /> Prior to release, a free public [[Software release life cycle#Beta|beta]] period ran from 4 August 2014 to 3 September 2014.<ref name=\"ign_beta\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://steamcommunity.com/games/301970/announcements/detail/260402200190503555|title=Screencheat Beta Is Closing - The Future & Your Reward|website=steamcommunity.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-20}}</ref> It was released for [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]] on 1 March 2016.<ref name=\"gamespot_console_release_date\" />\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = 71/100 (PC)<ref name=\"metacritic_pc\" /><br /> 69/100 (PS4)<ref name=\"metacritic_ps4\" /><br /> 72/100 (XBO)<ref name=\"metacritic_xbo\" />\n}}\n''Screencheat'' received an average reception from critics upon release.<ref name=\"metacritic_pc\" /><ref name=\"metacritic_ps4\" /><ref name=\"metacritic_xbo\" /> Critics praised the game for building an enjoyable experience around a single novel idea,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hookedgamers.com/pc/screencheat/review/article-1476.html|title=Screencheat PC review - \"Shooting into empty space\" {{!}} Hooked Gamers|website=www.hookedgamers.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/screencheat-review/|title=Screencheat review|work=pcgamer|access-date=2017-03-16|language=en}}</ref> but they also criticised the game's lack of depth, and limited replayability.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://multiplayer.it/recensioni/140480-screencheat-nascondersi-alla-luce.html|title=Nascondersi alla luce|work=Multiplayer.it|access-date=2017-03-16|language=it-IT}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitallydownloaded.net/2014/10/review-screen-cheat-pc.html|title=Review: Screencheat (PC)|last=S|first=Matt|website=www.digitallydownloaded.net|access-date=2017-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"ign_pc_release_date\">{{cite web | url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2014/09/25/screencheat-release-date-announced | title=Screencheat Release Date Announced | work=[[IGN]] | publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] | first=Katie | last=Williams | date=25 September 2014 | accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ign_beta\">{{cite web | url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2014/07/28/the-incoming-shooter-where-cheating-is-the-only-way-to-win | title=The Incoming Shooter Where Cheating is the Only Way to Win | work=[[IGN]] | publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] | first=Luke | last=Reilly| date=27 July 2014 | accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"gamespot_console_release_date\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/ps4xbox-one-game-that-encourages-screen-looking-ge/1100-6434636/ | title=PS4/Xbox One Game That Encourages Screen-Looking Gets Release Date | work=[[GameSpot]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | first=Eddie | last=Makuch | date=9 February 2016 | accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"metacritic_pc\">{{cite web | url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/screencheat | title=Screencheat for PC Reviews | work=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"metacritic_ps4\">{{cite web | url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/screencheat | title=Screencheat for PlayStation 4 Reviews | work=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate=2 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"metacritic_xbo\">{{cite web | url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/screencheat | title=Screencheat for Xbox One Reviews | work=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate=2 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://samuraipunk.com/screencheat/}}\n\n[[Category:2014 video games]]\n[[Category:First-person shooters]]\n[[Category:Game jam video games]]\n[[Category:Linux games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Unity (game engine) games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Australia]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = Screencheat\n| image = Screencheat Logo.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = ''Screencheat'''s logo\n| developer = Samurai Punk\n| publisher = Surprise Attack\n| series = \n| engine = [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]]\n| platforms = {{Unbulleted list|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[OS X]]|[[Linux]]|[[PlayStation 4]]|[[Xbox One]]|[[Nintendo Switch]]}}\n| released = {{ubl|'''Windows''', '''OS X''', '''Linux'''|21 October 2014|'''PS4''', '''Xbox One'''|1 March 2016|'''Nintendo Switch'''|29 November 2018}}\n| genre = [[First-person shooter]]\n| modes = [[Singleplayer]],  [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Screencheat''''' is a [[first-person shooter]] [[video game]] developed by Samurai Punk and published by Surprise Attack. The game was released for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[OS X]], and [[Linux]] in October 2014 and was released for [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]] in March 2016. The game was later ported to [[Nintendo Switch]], with enhanced graphics and updated interface, under the name '''''Screencheat: Unplugged''''', in November 2018.\n\n==Gameplay==\n''Screencheat'' is a [[multiplayer]] [[first-person shooter]] video game, in which every player's character model is invisible. However, the viewpoints of all players are shown on the screen, encouraging players [[Glossary of video game terms#screen cheat|to use this feature to deduce their opponents' location]].<ref name=\"ign_beta\" /> The maps are brightly colored in order to make it easier to figure out where a player is.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/03/04/screencheat-review-split-screen-revenge-5732508/|title=Games review: Screencheat is a celebration of split-screen gaming|last=Metro.co.uk|first=GameCentral for|date=2016-03-04|website=Metro|access-date=2017-03-24}}</ref>\n\n''Screencheat'' includes several different gamemodes. Some, including Deathmatch, King of the Hill, and Capture the Fun (where players fight for possession of a pi\u00f1ata), are multiplayer FPS standards.  The game also has a handful of unique gamemodes, such as One Shot, where each player is limited to one shot and cannot reload until a certain amount of time, and Murder Mystery, in which players have to kill a specific opponent with a particular weapon.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Development and release==\n''Screencheat'' was developed by Australia-based studio Samurai Punk and published by Surprise Attack.<ref name=\"ign_beta\" /> The game{{'}}s inception came from the 2014 [[Global Game Jam]], where it received several awards and honourable mentions.<ref name=\"ign_beta\" /> The game was released for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[OS X]], and [[Linux]] on 21 October 2014.<ref name=\"ign_pc_release_date\" /> Prior to release, a free public [[Software release life cycle#Beta|beta]] period ran from 4 August 2014 to 3 September 2014.<ref name=\"ign_beta\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://steamcommunity.com/games/301970/announcements/detail/260402200190503555|title=Screencheat Beta Is Closing - The Future & Your Reward|website=steamcommunity.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-20}}</ref> It was released for [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]] on 1 March 2016.<ref name=\"gamespot_console_release_date\" />\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = 71/100 (PC)<ref name=\"metacritic_pc\" /><br /> 69/100 (PS4)<ref name=\"metacritic_ps4\" /><br /> 72/100 (XBO)<ref name=\"metacritic_xbo\" />\n}}\n''Screencheat'' received an average reception from critics upon release.<ref name=\"metacritic_pc\" /><ref name=\"metacritic_ps4\" /><ref name=\"metacritic_xbo\" /> Critics praised the game for building an enjoyable experience around a single novel idea,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hookedgamers.com/pc/screencheat/review/article-1476.html|title=Screencheat PC review - \"Shooting into empty space\" {{!}} Hooked Gamers|website=www.hookedgamers.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/screencheat-review/|title=Screencheat review|work=pcgamer|access-date=2017-03-16|language=en}}</ref> but they also criticised the game's lack of depth, and limited replayability.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://multiplayer.it/recensioni/140480-screencheat-nascondersi-alla-luce.html|title=Nascondersi alla luce|work=Multiplayer.it|access-date=2017-03-16|language=it-IT}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitallydownloaded.net/2014/10/review-screen-cheat-pc.html|title=Review: Screencheat (PC)|last=S|first=Matt|website=www.digitallydownloaded.net|access-date=2017-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"ign_pc_release_date\">{{cite web | url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2014/09/25/screencheat-release-date-announced | title=Screencheat Release Date Announced | work=[[IGN]] | publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] | first=Katie | last=Williams | date=25 September 2014 | accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ign_beta\">{{cite web | url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2014/07/28/the-incoming-shooter-where-cheating-is-the-only-way-to-win | title=The Incoming Shooter Where Cheating is the Only Way to Win | work=[[IGN]] | publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] | first=Luke | last=Reilly| date=27 July 2014 | accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"gamespot_console_release